[[File:Fabiola_cabeza_de_baca.png|thumb|Fabiola Cabeza de Baca in front of a rural school in New Mexico, circa 1920s.]]
'''Fabiola Cabeza de Baca Gilbert''' (May 16, 1894 - October 14, 1991) was an [[United States|American]] educator, nutritionist, activist and writer. Cabeza de Baca is also known as the inventor of the u-shaped fried [[taco]] shell.{{Sfn|Rudnick|2012|p=72}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yvtPCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA574&ots=XW7rugpdWA&dq=%22fabiola%20cabeza%20de%20baca%22%20taco&pg=PA575#v=onepage&q=%22fabiola%20cabeza%20de%20baca%22%20taco&f=false|title=Iconic Mexico: An Encyclopedia From Acapulco to Zocalo|last=Pilcher|first=Jeffrey|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2015|isbn=9781610690447|editor-last=Zolov|editor-first=Eric|location=Santa Barbara, California|pages=574|chapter=Taco|quote=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yvtPCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA574&dq=%22fabiola%20cabeza%20de%20baca%22%20taco&pg=PA574#v=onepage&q=%22fabiola%20cabeza%20de%20baca%22%20taco&f=false|title=Iconic Mexico: An Encyclopedia from Acapulco to Zocalo|last=Pilcher|first=Jeffrey|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2015|isbn=9781610690447|editor-last=Zolov|editor-first=Eric|location=Santa Barbara, California|pages=574|chapter=Taco|quote=|via=}}</ref> She was also the first known published author of a cookbook describing [[New Mexican cuisine]].<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sfreporter.com/santafe/article-9385-origins-of-southwest-food.html|title=Origins of Southwest Food|last=DeWalt|first=Rob|date=22 October 2014|work=Santa Fe Reporter|access-date=24 January 2017|via=}}</ref> Cabeza de Baca was fluent in [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[English language|English]], [[Tewa language|Tewa]] and [[Tiwa people|Tiwa]].<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=http://plainshumanities.unl.edu/encyclopedia/doc/egp.ha.011|title=De Baca, Fabiola Cabeza (1898-1933)|last=McShane|first=Becky Jo|date=|editor-last=Wishart|editor-first=David J.|website=Encyclopedia of the Great Plains|publisher=University of Nebraska-Lincoln|access-date=24 January 2017}}</ref>

== Biography ==
Cabeza de Baca was part of a prominent New Mexican family and one of four siblings.<ref name=":1" /> She was a descendant of [[Spain|Spanish]] explorer, [[Álvar Núñez Cabeza de Vaca|Alvar Nuñez Cabeza de Baca]].{{Sfn|Rudnick|2012|p=72}} Her paternal great-grandfather was awarded the title to the Las Vegas Grandes land grant in 1823.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://newmexicohistory.org/people/fabiola-cabeza-de-baca|title=Fabiola Cabeza de Baca|last=Sullivan|first=Michael Ann|date=|website=New Mexico History.org|publisher=|access-date=24 January 2017}}</ref> She was also related to the second Governor of New Mexico, [[Ezequiel Cabeza De Baca|Ezequiel Cabeza de Baca]], who was her uncle.<ref name=":1" /> Cabeza de Baca was born in and lived part of her life [[Las Vegas, New Mexico]].{{Sfn|Rudnick|2012|p=72}} She also grew up on a [[ranch]] in La Liendre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nmwomensforum.com/images/NewMexicoHistoricWomenMarkers.pdf|title=New Mexico Historic Women Marker Initiative|last=|first=|date=|website=New Mexico Women's Forum|publisher=|access-date=24 January 2017}}</ref> Her mother died when she was four, and her paternal grandmother raised her afterwards.<ref name=":2" /> Her grandmother instilled the idea of "[[Noblesse oblige|''nobless oblige'']]" in Cabeza de Baca.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_62IjQ-XQScC&lpg=PA104&dq=%22fabiola%20cabeza%20de%20baca%22&pg=PA104#v=onepage&q=%22fabiola%20cabeza%20de%20baca%22&f=false|title=Latinas in the United States: A Historical Encyclopedia|last=Pounce|first=Merrihelen|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2006|isbn=9780253111692|editor-last=Ruiz|editor-first=Vicki L.|volume=1|location=Bloomington|pages=104–105|chapter=Cabeza de Baca, Fabiola (1894-1991)|quote=|editor-last2=Korrol|editor-first2=Virginia Sanchez|via=}}</ref> As a young woman, Cabeza de Baca "refused to take on her 'proper' role as a Spanish lady" and spent her time riding horses and watching the ranch men work.{{Sfn|Rudnick|2012|p=72}} When she was twelve, she visited [[Spain]].{{Sfn|Davis|2000|p=61}}

Cabeza de Baca first attended a [[Catholic school]], where she was expelled from Loreto Academy's [[kindergarten]] for slapping a [[nun]].{{Sfn|Rudnick|2012|p=72}}<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":0" /> She later went to New Mexico Normal College, where she earned her teaching certificate in 1912.{{Sfn|Rudnick|2012|p=72}} In the year of her graduation, her family was nearly [[Bankruptcy|bankrupt]] because of serious economic hardships.{{Sfn|Davis|2000|p=61}} In 1921 she earned a bachelor's degree in [[pedagogy]] and visited Spain a second time.{{Sfn|Davis|2000|p=61}} Later, she would earn a second bachelor's degree in [[home economics]] from [[New Mexico State University]] (NMSU) in 1929.{{Sfn|Davis|2000|p=61}}

Her first job was teaching in a one-room schoolhouse in 1916.<ref name=":1" /> Her father was opposed to her teaching, but she insisted.<ref name=":1" /> She continued to teach school in the New Mexico public school system for a few years, and after receiving her degree from NMSU, began to work as an [[Agricultural extension|extension agent]] for [[Hispanic]] and [[Pueblo]] villages in New Mexico<ref name=":2" /> as part of the New Mexico [[Agricultural extension|Agricultural Extension Service]] (NMAES). Her career as an extension agent for these villages would span thirty years.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web|url=http://myhero.com/hero.asp?hero=F_CabezadeBaca_2013|title=Fabiola Cabeza de Baca Gilbert|last=Navajas|first=Emma|date=|website=My Hero|publisher=|access-date=24 January 2017}}</ref> In this capacity, she taught rural women modern [[Agriculture|agricultural]] techniques, introduced modern devices like [[sewing machine]]s, so that rural families could thrive on their own land.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web|url=http://www.route66women.com/portfolio/fabiola-cabeza-de-baca/|title=Fabiola Cabeza de Baca|last=|first=|date=|website=The Women on the Mother Road|publisher=|access-date=24 January 2017}}</ref> She also helped organize clubs for rural women.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.santafenewmexican.com/news/local_news/santa-fe-th-work-words-formed-sense-of-place/article_dce752c1-ffc1-50c2-beb2-8a992ff7aaa3.html|title=Santa Fe 400th: Work, Words Formed Sense of Place|last=Dean|first=Rob|date=1 May 2010|work=Santa Fe New Mexican|access-date=24 January 2017|via=}}</ref> She was the first extension agent who spoke [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and often translated government information into Spanish for rural residents.<ref name=":1" /> She was also the first agent sent out to Pueblos.{{Sfn|Davis|2000|p=62}}

While visiting homes, she collected cultural information, recipes, stories and more.<ref name=":1" /> Some of these were published in the Santa Fe ''Nuevo Mexicana''.<ref name=":1" /> She also hosted a [[Multilingualism|bilingual]]<ref name=":5" /> weekly radio show related to [[homemaking]] on the station, [[KVSF-FM|KVSF]].<ref name=":1" />

In 1929, she [[Elopement|eloped]] with Carlos Gilbert, an insurance agent and member of the [[League of United Latin American Citizens]] (LULAC).{{Sfn|Rudnick|2012|p=74}} The match was not approved of by her father,{{Sfn|Rudnick|2012|p=74}} and the couple divorced after 10 years.<ref name=":1" /> Her husband's activism affected Cabeza de Baca, who became involved with Hispanic [[Civil and political rights|civil rights]].<ref name=":1" />

In 1932, she was injured by a train car, which resulted in having one of her legs [[Amputation|amputated]].{{Sfn|Rudnick|2012|p=75}} While she recovered for a period of two years, she continued to write and eventually returned to work, visiting homes.<ref name=":1" /> In 1935, she and several other women founded  [[La Sociedad Folklorica]] in Santa Fe as an organization "dedicated to preserving Spanish Language and Hispanic traditions in Santa Fe."<ref name=":4" /> During [[World War II]], she helped women create [[Victory Gardens]] and set up [[Child care|childcare]] for women who were working.<ref name=":0" /> In 1950, [[UNESCO]] sent Cabeza de Baca to [[Pátzcuaro]] to teach modern food and agriculture techniques to students.{{Sfn|Davis|2000|p=62}} In 1959, she retired from working as an extension agent.<ref name=":1" />

In her retirement, she continued to preserve Spanish culture and was involved with the La Sociedad Folklorica of Santa Fe.<ref name=":1" /> She was also active in the [[Peace Corps]].<ref name=":5" />

In May 1984, she entered into a [[Nursing home care|nursing home]].{{Sfn|Davis|2000|p=62}} On October 14, 1991, Cabeza de Baca died in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico|Albuquerque]].<ref name=":1" /> She was buried near [[Newkirk, New Mexico]] on the family's ranch.{{Sfn|Davis|2000|p=62}}

== Writing ==
Her book, ''Historic Cookery'', first published in 1931, collected traditional [[recipe]]s from the area, emphasizing "basic New Mexico foods."{{Sfn|Davis|2000|p=62}} It was written with an "Anglo audience in mind."{{Sfn|Davis|2000|p=63}} ''Historic Cookery'' also marked the first time that New Mexican recipes were written down with "exact measurements."<ref name=":3" /> In 1959, Cabeza de Baca and chef as the Alvarado Hotel worked to update the recipes in ''Historic Cookery'' to modern techniques.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/8540488//|title=Baile Antiguo|last=|first=|date=10 April 1959|work=Albuquerque Journal|access-date=24 January 2017|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The book sold over 100,000 copies,{{Sfn|Rudnick|2012|p=73}} and was republished many times.<ref name=":1" /> A copy of this book was sent to the governor of each state in the US by [[Thomas J. Mabry|Thomas Mabry]] along with a bag of [[pinto bean]]s.{{Sfn|Rudnick|2012|p=73}} Her work helped introduce cooking with [[Chili pepper|chile]] to the American public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tastetalks.com/cinco-de-mayo-mexican-food-1778851953.html|title=Let's Give More Credit to Mexican Chefs, Shall We?|last=Finney|first=Teresa|date=5 May 2016|website=Taste Talks|publisher=|access-date=24 January 2017}}</ref>

Cabeza de Baca's second cookbook, ''The Good Life: New Mexico Traditions and Foods'' was first published in 1949 and was one of the first cookbooks to "place recipes within the historic and cultural contexts out of which they grew."{{Sfn|Rudnick|2012|p=73-74}} The book contained a fictional family, the Turrieta family, which represented the people that she met as an extension agent.<ref name=":1" /> The book also describes regional differences in [[New Mexican cuisine]].{{Sfn|Davis|2000|p=63}}

Her [[Autobiography|autobiographical]] narrative, ''We Fed Them Cactus'' (1954), describes the life of New Mexican [[Hispanos]],<ref name=":2" /> and documents four generations of her family.<ref name=":1" /> The title refers to a major drought that caused her family to have to feed [[cactus]] to their [[cattle]].<ref name=":2" /> The story is narrated by El Cuate, or the camp cook, and the narrative in ''We Fed Them Cactus'' is meant to "counter Anglo-American stereotyping of wealthy and corrupt landowners of the ''rico'' class."{{Sfn|Davis|2000|p=63}}

Between 1958 and 1961 she wrote and edited for a magazine she helped found, the ''Santa Fe Scene''.{{Sfn|Davis|2000|p=62}}

Later [[Chicano]] readings of Cabeza de Baca's work were critical of her writing, which was seen as "elitist and not representative of the realistic Chicano experience."{{Sfn|Davis|2000|p=64}} Despite this criticism, her writing has been viewed by Hispanic literary critics as a precursor to [[Xicana literature|Chicana literature]].<ref name=":0" />

